….. Propose a dividend of N2.35k per share value N19.4bn will go to shareholders (L-R): Jordi Borrut Bel, managing director/chief executive officer; Kola Jamodu, CFR, chairman and Uaboi Agbebaku, company secretary/legal adviser, all of Nigerian Breweries Plc. at the 72ndAnnual General Meeting of the Company on Friday in Lagos. Nigerian Breweries Plc (NB plc) has announced a profit after tax (PAT) of N19.4 billion for the 2018 financial year as against N324.4 billion during the year under review.  According to its audited financial results released on Monday to the Nigerian Stock Exchange by Uaboi Agbebaku, the company’s legal director, said after-tax profit recorded in 2018 was lower than the N31.6 billion recorded in 2017 representing a 41 percent decline.  The report showed the revenue dipped from N344.5 billion recorded in 2017 to N324.4 billion in 2018, representing a six percent decline.  In the statement, the Company’s finances were “adversely impacted” by the increased excise duty rates that came into effect during the year, as well as a “challenging operating environment”.  The Company’s Board of Directors will propose a dividend declaration to the tune of N19.4 billion to its shareholders during its annual general meeting coming up on May 17, 2019.  This amount figure would represent N2.43k per share, which means a hundred percent dividend payout ratio or otherwise call repatriating of fund by investor(s).  In 2018, Nigerian Breweries had paid an interim dividend of N4.8 billion which amounted to N0.60k per share, thus translating to a final dividend of N14.6 billion or N1.83k per share.  The statement said if the proposed final dividend is approved, it will become payable on May 20 to all shareholders whose names appear on the company’s register of members, at the close of business on March 6.  Amehnews recall that some time ago, the federal government in order to increase its fiscal revenues, had introduced a new excise duty regime which went into effect in June 2018 and would last till 2020.  Under the regime, beer and stout will attract 0.30k per centilitre (Cl) in 2018 and 0.35k per Cl each in 2019 and 2020. 